Executive Summary¶

The COVID-19 pandemic has had a profound impact on societies worldwide. Despite the hight of the pandemic being behind us, understanding the patterns and dynamics of its spread is crucial for effective mitigation and response strategies should a similar pandemic occur again in the future. In this study, we leverage census data and state-level COVID-19 statistics to gain insights into the geographic variations and factors influencing the spread of the virus within the United States. Through our analysis, we found that the implementation of policies to prevent the spread of COVID-19 varied across states, resulting in differing levels of confirmed cases. However, the percentage of the population that died showed less variation, suggesting consistent policies for recovery and treatment. We also observed that the number of cases and deaths did not follow a linear correlation with state population, indicating the presence of unique dynamics for states of different population sizes. Lastly, our study highlighted the impact of multiple waves of COVID-19 on states with the highest and lowest percentages of cases and deaths, providing valuable insights for future pandemic management strategies. To improve our study, we can include mobility and transportation data from the census to gain insights into people's movement, and effectively, the transmission of the pandemic.

Problem Statement¶

In this report we want to answer the question,

What insights can we get regarding the spread of the Covid pandemic in the US using census data and the number of cases for each state and are there particular states of interest in the dataset?

Motivation¶

The COVID-19 pandemic has posed unprecedented challenges worldwide, impacting all aspects of society. But while the peak of the COVID-19 pandemic seems to have already passed, it is still important to uncover insights and continue to study the events that transpired and how it progressed. Understanding the underlying factors contributing to the spread of COVID-19 within different states can assist health authorities in developing effective mitigation measures and allocating resources where they are most needed in the future. In this study we focus our attention to census data to identify population characteristics and invection rates observed in different states.

Data Source¶

Our dataset is taken from Amazon Web Service's marketplace. We accessed it directly with Amazon Web Service's EMR.

Safegraph Open Census Data

The SafeGraph Open Census Data on AWS is a comprehensive dataset that provides information on population movement and demographics alongside data on the COVID-19 pandemic. It offers valuable insights into various geographic areas and can be used for various analytical purposes.

Filepath: covid19-lake/safegraph-open-census-data/

Dataset Overview:

Dataset Name: SafeGraph Open Census Data Source: Amazon Web Services

Contents:

  • Anonymized and aggregated data on population movement
  • Demographic information related to different geographic locations
  • Valuable insights and statistics on population distribution and mobility
  • COVID-related data involving cases and deaths

Original Data Source:

The SafeGraph Open Census Data on AWS is derived from a variety of sources, including mobile applications, GPS data, and other location-based services. The data is processed and made available through the SafeGraph platform, which specializes in location data analysis.

Accessing the Dataset:

To access the SafeGraph Open Census Data on AWS, you can navigate to the AWS platform and search for the dataset using the appropriate keywords or identifiers. The dataset may be available for download or accessible through specific AWS services, such as Amazon S3. SafeGraph as well has their own site containing the data.

Data Exploration¶

As said earlier, there are two parts in this dataset - one on census data and the other on COVID data. The census data is divided into file type-based categories - CSVs and JSONs, which contains all sorts of tables labeled with coded headers. The coded headers correspond to different things. The first six characters refer to the type of table's contents featured and the latter characters referring to area/location. For example if you have a header name/title being "B08303m13", it would be "Travel Time to Work Residence 1 Year Ago in the Combined New England City and Town Area" with B08303 referring to "TRAVEL TIME TO WORK" and m13 referring to "Residence 1 Year Ago - Combined New England City and Town Area". The table below details some of what is in the data dictionaries.

Data Pre-Processing

  1. Loaded the player attributes raw data from Table 1 as tot_pop_df using the specified census file path.
  2. Converted the tot_pop_df DataFrame to Pandas DataFrame using .toPandas() for inspection and analysis.
  3. Loaded the COVID-19 data from Table 2 as covid_df using the provided COVID file path.
  4. Grouped the tot_pop_df DataFrame by state, calculating the sum of population (B01003e1) for each state using .groupBy() and .agg().
  5. Ordered the grouped DataFrame by the state code (fips) in ascending order.
  6. Converted the grouped DataFrame _df to Pandas DataFrame _pdf using .toPandas() for further analysis.
  7. Converted the COVID-19 DataFrame covid_df to Pandas DataFrame cv_pdf using .toPandas() for further analysis.
  8. Joined the COVID-19 DataFrame covid_df with the grouped DataFrame _df on the state code (fips) using .join().
  9. Ordered the merged DataFrame by date in ascending order using .orderBy().
  10. Calculated the percentage of COVID-19 cases and deaths relative to the total population, creating new columns case_pct and death_pct using .withColumn().
  11. Converted the merged DataFrame merged to Pandas DataFrame merged_pdf using .toPandas() for analysis and visualization purposes.

                       col('cases') / col('sum(B01003e1)') * 100)
          .withColumn('death_pct', 
                       col('deaths') / col('sum(B01003e1)') * 100))
merged_pdf = merged.toPandas()

Methodology¶

Firstly, the census data containing population information and the COVID-19 data with case and death counts are loaded. Next, the datasets are merged based on the FIPS code, to get the total population and COVID-19 information for each state. We then calculated the percentage of cases per state with respect to the total population which can be calculated from the total number of cases aggregated per state, which is divided by the corresponding population. We looked at boxplots to identify outliers in terms of percentage of cases and deaths. To explore the time series aspect, states with the highest and lowest case percentages are identified and compared to see how these states responded to the waves of COVID-19.

Descriptive Analytics¶

In this section, we will look at the condition of the differnt states from different angles.

Results and Discussions¶

We found several insights during the exploration of the dataset. Firstly, we found that the different states likely had varying degrees of implementation with regards to policies preventing the spread of the pandemic which is why we see outliers in the percentage of the population that are confirmed cases. But despite this, we see no outliers in terms of the percentage of the population that died. This suggests that policies regarding COVID-19 recovery and treatment were likely more strictly implemented for all states. We also found that the number of cases and deaths are not linearly correlated with the total population of the state. This implies that there are different dynamics at play with regards to preventing cases and deaths as the population increases. Lastly, we looked at the progression of the percentage of cases and deaths for the states with the highest and lowest percentage and saw how those states were differently affected by the multiple waves of covid cases.

Conclusion¶

In this report, we uncovered several notable insights. Firstly, we found that the implementation of policies aimed at preventing the spread of the pandemic varied across different states. This this can be seen from the presence of outliers in the percentage of confirmed cases with respect to the total population. However, when examining the percentage of the population that died, no outliers were observed. This suggests that policies pertaining to COVID-19 recovery and treatment were likely uniformly enforced across states. We also discovered that the number of cases and deaths did not exhibit a linear correlation with the total population of a state. It is worth noting that despite California having the largest population, it did not possess the highest percentage of cases or deaths. This observation highlights that population size alone does not dictate the severity of the pandemic's impact on a state. Lastly, we analyzed the progression of the percentage of cases and deaths in states with the highest and lowest percentages. Rhode Island emerged as the state with the highest percentage of cases, while Maryland had the lowest percentage. In terms of the percentage of deaths, Arizona exhibited the highest rate, whereas Hawaii recorded the lowest. Our analysis of the trends showed the effects of the multiple waves of COVID-19 cases across different states, emphasizing the importance of considering local factors and tailored approaches in managing the pandemic.

Recommendations¶

One detail that this report missed and didn't have data for, is the area of the state or the population density. It makes more sense for states with higher populations to have less problems with social distancing if they have the excess land area available to them. To improve this study further we suggest exploring the following suggestions:

  1. Include geospatial data to get the population density instead of simply using the total population to approximate interaction.
  2. We can include data like mobility and transport from the census data to have a better idea of how people move and how the pandemic spreads through this.
